======================================================================
PART 1: THE DIGIT-SHIFT PRINCIPLE
    1 → (10, 11) in base b means 1 → (b, b+1)
======================================================================

In base b, the digit '1' shifted one position left gives 'b'.
Adding '1' in the units place gives 'b+1'.
So '10' and '11' (in base b) are (b, b+1).

The user's insight: '10 and 11 are both similar to 1, shifted over a digit'

  Base  |  '10'_b  |  '11'_b  |  Pair
  ------+----------+----------+-------
     2  |       2  |       3  |  (2, 3)
     3  |       3  |       4  |  (3, 4)
     4  |       4  |       5  |  (4, 5)
     5  |       5  |       6  |  (5, 6)
     6  |       6  |       7  |  (6, 7)
     7  |       7  |       8  |  (7, 8)
     8  |       8  |       9  |  (8, 9)
     9  |       9  |      10  |  (9, 10)
    10  |      10  |      11  |  (10, 11)
    11  |      11  |      12  |  (11, 12)
    12  |      12  |      13  |  (12, 13)

KEY OBSERVATIONS:
  Base 2:  '10'=2, '11'=3    ← THE FUNDAMENTAL PAIR
  Base 7:  '10'=7, '11'=8    ← THE TRANSITION PAIR
  Base 10: '10'=10, '11'=11  ← THE DECIMAL PAIR

So the user's three levels of (b, b+1) pairs are:
  Level 0:  (2, 3)   — base 2 (binary)
  Level 1:  (7, 8)   — base 7
  Level 2:  (10, 11) — base 10 (our numeral system)

And WHY base 7?  Because 7 = 2³ - 1 and 8 = 2³.
The 'shift' from Level 0 to Level 1 is exponentiation: 2³.

THE CHAIN OF SHIFTS:
  1  →  (1·2, 1·2+1)  =  (2, 3)
  2³ - 1  =  7
  2³      =  8
  So (7,8) = (2³-1, 2³)

  And 10 = 2+8 = 2+2³ = 2(1+2²) = 2·5
  And 11 = 3+8 = 3+2³  — also 11 is prime!

BINARY REPRESENTATIONS:
    1 =      0b1  (binary)
    2 =     0b10  (binary)
    3 =     0b11  (binary)
    7 =    0b111  (binary)
    8 =   0b1000  (binary)
   10 =   0b1010  (binary)
   11 =   0b1011  (binary)

  1  = 1       (1 bit)
  2  = 10      (1 shifted left 1)
  3  = 11      (1 shifted left 1, plus 1)
  7  = 111     (all ones, 3 bits)
  8  = 1000    (1 shifted left 3)
  10 = 1010    (interleaved: 1_1_)
  11 = 1011    (interleaved: 1_11)

  PATTERN: 10 = 1010₂ = '10' with '10' interleaved!
           11 = 1011₂ = '10' with '11' interleaved!
  So 10 and 11 carry the (2,3) pattern within their binary form.

