======================================================================
PART 3: THE 7-8 BOUNDARY IN RECURRENCE SPACE
    (already explored by S71d — extending here)
======================================================================

Jacobsthal sequence J(n) = (2^n - (-1)^n) / 3:

  J( 1) =        1  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 1)
  J( 2) =        1  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 1)
  J( 3) =        3  (mod 7: 3, mod 8: 3)
  J( 4) =        5  (mod 7: 5, mod 8: 5)
  J( 5) =       11  (mod 7: 4, mod 8: 3)
  J( 6) =       21  (mod 7: 0, mod 8: 5)
  J( 7) =       43  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 3)
  J( 8) =       85  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 5)
  J( 9) =      171  (mod 7: 3, mod 8: 3)
  J(10) =      341  (mod 7: 5, mod 8: 5)
  J(11) =      683  (mod 7: 4, mod 8: 3)
  J(12) =     1365  (mod 7: 0, mod 8: 5)
  J(13) =     2731  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 3)
  J(14) =     5461  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 5)
  J(15) =    10923  (mod 7: 3, mod 8: 3)
  J(16) =    21845  (mod 7: 5, mod 8: 5)
  J(17) =    43691  (mod 7: 4, mod 8: 3)
  J(18) =    87381  (mod 7: 0, mod 8: 5)
  J(19) =   174763  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 3)
  J(20) =   349525  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 5)

Jacobsthal-Lucas j(n) = 2^n + (-1)^n:

  j( 1) =        1  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 1)
  j( 2) =        5  (mod 7: 5, mod 8: 5)
  j( 3) =        7  (mod 7: 0, mod 8: 7)
  j( 4) =       17  (mod 7: 3, mod 8: 1)
  j( 5) =       31  (mod 7: 3, mod 8: 7)
  j( 6) =       65  (mod 7: 2, mod 8: 1)
  j( 7) =      127  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 7)
  j( 8) =      257  (mod 7: 5, mod 8: 1)
  j( 9) =      511  (mod 7: 0, mod 8: 7)
  j(10) =     1025  (mod 7: 3, mod 8: 1)
  j(11) =     2047  (mod 7: 3, mod 8: 7)
  j(12) =     4097  (mod 7: 2, mod 8: 1)
  j(13) =     8191  (mod 7: 1, mod 8: 7)
  j(14) =    16385  (mod 7: 5, mod 8: 1)

  j(3) = 7    ← Jacobsthal-Lucas at n=3 gives 7!
  j(3) = 2³ + (-1)³ = 8 - 1 = 7
  So 7 IS the Jacobsthal-Lucas value at n=3.
  And 8 = 2³ is the pure power.

  The pair (7,8) = (j(3), 2³) = (Jacobsthal-Lucas, pure power)
  Similarly: (1,2) = (j(1), 2¹), (3,4) = (j(2), 2²), (7,8) = (j(3), 2³)

  The (j(k), 2^k) pairs:
    k=1: (j(1), 2^1) = (1, 2)
    k=2: (j(2), 2^2) = (5, 4)
    k=3: (j(3), 2^3) = (7, 8)
    k=4: (j(4), 2^4) = (17, 16)
    k=5: (j(5), 2^5) = (31, 32)
    k=6: (j(6), 2^6) = (65, 64)
    k=7: (j(7), 2^7) = (127, 128)

WHERE ARE 10 AND 11 IN THIS?
  10 = 2·5 = 2·(2²+1)
  11 = prime
  10 = j(?) — solve 2^k + (-1)^k = 10:
    k even: 2^k + 1 = 10 → 2^k = 9 → no integer k
    k odd:  2^k - 1 = 10 → 2^k = 11 → no integer k
  So 10 is NOT a Jacobsthal-Lucas value.

  But 10 = k(k-1) for k? Solve k²-k=10: k = (1+√41)/2 ≈ 3.70. No.
  11 = k(k-1)? k²-k=11: k = (1+√45)/2 ≈ 3.85. No.

  The Jacobsthal x = k(k-1) series:
  k=1: x=0   (trivial)
  k=2: x=2   (the OCF!)
  k=3: x=6   (6-spectrum)
  k=4: x=12  (12-spectrum)
  k=5: x=20
  k=6: x=30

  I(CG, 10) and I(CG, 11): the Jacobsthal recurrence at x=10,11:
  x=10: J_10(n) = (r^n - s^n)/(r-s) where r,s = (1±√41)/2
         r = (1+√41)/2 ≈ 3.70
         NOT an integer root!

  x=11: r = (1+√45)/2 = (1+3√5)/2 ≈ 3.85
         NOT an integer root!

  BUT: x=12 gives k=4, root=4 (integer!)
  So 10 and 11 sit BETWEEN the integer-root values x=6 (k=3) and x=12 (k=4).

======================================================================
PART 4: 10 AND 11 IN TOURNAMENT THEORY — THE DECIMAL VIEW
======================================================================

Tournament counts:
  n= 3:                    8 tournaments (2^3)
  n= 4:                   64 tournaments (2^6)
  n= 5:                 1024 tournaments (2^10)
  n= 6:                32768 tournaments (2^15)
  n= 7:              2097152 tournaments (2^21)
  n= 8:            268435456 tournaments (2^28)
  n= 9:          68719476736 tournaments (2^36)
  n=10:       35184372088832 tournaments (2^45)
  n=11:    36028797018963968 tournaments (2^55)
  n=12: 73786976294838206464 tournaments (2^66)
  n=13: 302231454903657293676544 tournaments (2^78)

At n=10: 2^45 ≈ 3.5×10¹³ tournaments
At n=11: 2^55 ≈ 3.6×10¹⁶ tournaments

Max independent set size = floor((n-1)/2) for CG(T):
  n= 3: max α from 3-cycles alone = 1
  n= 4: max α from 3-cycles alone = 1
  n= 5: max α from 3-cycles alone = 1
  n= 6: max α from 3-cycles alone = 2
  n= 7: max α from 3-cycles alone = 2
  n= 8: max α from 3-cycles alone = 2
  n= 9: max α from 3-cycles alone = 3
  n=10: max α from 3-cycles alone = 3
  n=11: max α from 3-cycles alone = 3
  n=12: max α from 3-cycles alone = 4
  n=13: max α from 3-cycles alone = 4

At n=10: up to 3 disjoint 3-cycles (using 9 of 10 vertices)
         plus a possible 5-cycle using shared vertices... but no,
         disjoint means no shared vertices.
         3 disjoint 3-cycles use 9 vertices; one left over.
         Or: 1 five-cycle + 1 three-cycle + 2 left over = possible
         Or: 2 five-cycles = 10 vertices exactly! α₂ with both 5-cycles!

At n=11: 3 disjoint 3-cycles (9 verts) + 1 extra vertex (no cycle)
         Or: 2 five-cycles + 1 vertex = α₂
         Or: 1 seven-cycle + 1 three-cycle + 1 vertex = α₂
         Or: 1 five-cycle + 2 three-cycles (5+3+3=11) = α₃!
         NEW: n=11 is the FIRST where α₃ involves all vertices!

CYCLE PACKING STRUCTURES:

n=10 (= 2·5 = 2·(2²+1)):
  α_3: 3×3 (uses 9/10, 1 free)
  α_2: 2×3 (uses 6/10, 4 free)
  α_2: 1×3+1×5 (uses 8/10, 2 free)
  α_2: 2×5 (uses 10/10, 0 free)
  α_2: 1×3+1×7 (uses 10/10, 0 free)
  α_1: 1×3 (uses 3/10, 7 free)
  α_1: 1×5 (uses 5/10, 5 free)
  α_1: 1×7 (uses 7/10, 3 free)
  α_1: 1×9 (uses 9/10, 1 free)

n=11 (prime, = 2³ + 3 = 8 + 3):
  α_3: 3×3 (uses 9/11, 2 free)
  α_3: 2×3+1×5 (uses 11/11, 0 free)
  α_2: 2×3 (uses 6/11, 5 free)
  α_2: 1×3+1×5 (uses 8/11, 3 free)
  α_2: 2×5 (uses 10/11, 1 free)
  α_2: 1×3+1×7 (uses 10/11, 1 free)
  α_1: 1×3 (uses 3/11, 8 free)
  α_1: 1×5 (uses 5/11, 6 free)
  α_1: 1×7 (uses 7/11, 4 free)
  α_1: 1×9 (uses 9/11, 2 free)
  α_1: 1×11 (uses 11/11, 0 free)

CRITICAL: n=11 has a PERFECT PACKING: 1×5 + 2×3 = 11 (α₃, all vertices!)
          Also: 1×11 = 11 (a single Hamiltonian cycle!)
          n=11 is the first prime where 3+3+5 = n.

======================================================================
PART 5: THE BASE-b RECURRENCE TOWER
    For each base b, the pair (b, b+1) defines a recurrence level
======================================================================

UNIFIED FRAMEWORK:
  The Jacobsthal recurrence at x = b(b-1)/2... no.
  The FIBONACCI recurrence at x: f(n) = f(n-1) + x·f(n-2)
  has roots r = (1 + √(1+4x))/2, s = (1 - √(1+4x))/2

  For r to be an integer k, need 1+4x = (2k-1)² → x = k(k-1)

  x=b(b-1) table:
  b= 1: x = 1·0 =   0,  root = 1,  secondary = 0
  b= 2: x = 2·1 =   2,  root = 2,  secondary = -1
  b= 3: x = 3·2 =   6,  root = 3,  secondary = -2
  b= 4: x = 4·3 =  12,  root = 4,  secondary = -3
  b= 5: x = 5·4 =  20,  root = 5,  secondary = -4
  b= 6: x = 6·5 =  30,  root = 6,  secondary = -5
  b= 7: x = 7·6 =  42,  root = 7,  secondary = -6
  b= 8: x = 8·7 =  56,  root = 8,  secondary = -7
  b= 9: x = 9·8 =  72,  root = 9,  secondary = -8
  b=10: x = 10·9 =  90,  root = 10,  secondary = -9
  b=11: x = 11·10 = 110,  root = 11,  secondary = -10

  The 'digit 1 shifted' gives pairs:
  Base 2: x₂=2, x₃=6    → roots (2,-1) and (3,-2)
  Base 7: x₇=42, x₈=56  → roots (7,-6) and (8,-7)
  Base 10: x₁₀=90, x₁₁=110 → roots (10,-9) and (11,-10)

I(CG(T), x) at these special values — for ALL n≤5 tournaments:

  n=3 (8 tournaments):
    x=2(OCF)      : range [1, 3], 2 distinct values
    x=6(k=3)      : range [1, 7], 2 distinct values
    x=10          : range [1, 11], 2 distinct values
    x=11          : range [1, 12], 2 distinct values
    x=42(k=7)     : range [1, 43], 2 distinct values
