  H mod 10: only odd residues
  H mod 11: all residues?

DIVISIBILITY WEB:
  7 = 2³ - 1  (Mersenne)
  8 = 2³       (power of 2)
  10 = 2 × 5  (2 × (2²+1))
  11 = prime   (2³ + 3)
  21 = 3 × 7  (3 × Mersenne)
  24 = 8 × 3  (2³ × 3)
  56 = 8 × 7  (2³ × Mersenne)
  77 = 7 × 11 (Mersenne × prime)
  110 = 10 × 11

======================================================================
PART 11: THE RECURRENCE LATTICE — SEEING EVERYTHING AS RECURRENCES
======================================================================

Every key quantity in tournament theory satisfies a recurrence:

1. H(T) itself: deletion-contraction recurrence
   H(T) = Σ_{v→w in T} H(T-v, w→...)
   This is NOT a simple linear recurrence — it's tree-structured.

2. Jacobsthal: J(n) = J(n-1) + 2J(n-2)
   The 'template' recurrence with root 2.
   J(n) = (2ⁿ - (-1)ⁿ)/3

3. k-nacci: f(n) = Σᵢ₌₁ᵏ f(n-i)
   Root approaches 2 from below, rate 1/2 per step.

4. Weighted k-nacci: f(n) = Σᵢ₌₁ᵏ 2^{i-1}f(n-i)
   Root approaches 3 from below, rate 2/3 per step.

5. Tournament count: T(n) = 2^{n(n-1)/2}
   Recurrence: T(n) = 2^{n-1} · T(n-1)
   Root = ∞ (exponential in n)

6. I(CG, x): the independence polynomial
   Recurrence via deletion-contraction on CG:
   I(G, x) = I(G-v, x) + x·I(G-N[v], x)
   Root = 1+x for isolated vertex, approaching the chromatic root.

7. The Pfaffian: Pf(A-A^T)
   Recurrence: Pf(B) = Σⱼ (-1)^{j+1} B_{1j} Pf(B_{1j,1j})
   Expansion along first row.

8. det(I+xA): characteristic-like determinant
   Recurrence: cofactor expansion gives tree of subproblems.
   Coefficients c_k = signed cycle cover counts.

THE UNIFICATION:
  All roots in tournament theory live in Z[2,3]:
  • Jacobsthal roots: 2, -1 (= -1)
  • x=6 roots: 3, -2
  • x=12 roots: 4=2², -3
  • k-nacci limits: 2
  • w-k-nacci limits: 3
  • I(CG,x) isolated vertex weight: 1+x → 3 at x=2
  • Pfaffian: integer (lives in Z)
  • Q divisor: 8 = 2³

  The ONLY primes that appear as recurrence roots
  in tournament theory are 2 and 3.
  (And their negatives -1, -2, -3, ... which are
  the secondary roots of Jacobsthal recurrences.)

======================================================================
FINAL SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

THE HIERARCHY:

  Level 0: (1)     — the identity, the starting point
  Level 1: (2, 3)  — the two primes, in binary '10' and '11'
           These are '1 shifted by one digit'.
           2 = counting root, 3 = topological root

  Level 2: (7, 8)  — the transition, 2³-1 and 2³
           These are '1 shifted by three digits' in binary.
           7 = last pure (single-level) tournament size
           8 = first cross-level tournament size
           Also: Q = (H²-Pf²)/8, so 8 is the natural divisor.

  Level 3: (10, 11) — the interpolation, between Jacobsthal levels 3 and 4
           In binary: 1010 and 1011 = INTERLEAVING of (2,3)
           10 = 2+8 (Level 1 + Level 2)
           11 = 3+8 (Level 1 + Level 2)
           n=11: first perfect 3-part cycle packing (3+3+5=11)
           11 = 2³ + 3 (the sum of the two fundamental primes' tower)

  The chain: 1 → (2,3) → (7,8) → (10,11)
  encodes: identity → fundamental pair → cross-level threshold → interleaving

  And the rule:
    Each level = previous level shifted and combined.
    (2,3) = shift of 1
    (7,8) = 2³-tower of (2,3)
    (10,11) = (2+8, 3+8) = sum of levels 1 and 2

  In recurrence terms:
    k-nacci: φ_k → 2 at rate 1/2
    w-k-nacci: ψ_k → 3 at rate 2/3
    Ratio ψ_k/φ_k → 3/2 (the 'constant of tournament theory')
    These rates themselves form a geometric sequence: 1/2, 2/3, ... → 1

Done.
